cz.hobrasoft.pdfmu

Class PreferenceListComparator<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • cz.hobrasoft.pdfmu.PreferenceListComparator<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type of objects that may be compared by this comparator
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    MapSorter<T>, Comparator<T>

    public class PreferenceListComparator<T>
extends Object
implements Comparator<T>, MapSorter<T>
    Orders the items by a preference list.

    The items at the start of the preference list are placed before (that is deemed smaller than) the other items. The items that appear in the preference list are placed before the items that do not appear in the preference list. The order of items that do not appear in the preference list is not specified (and is application specific in practice). Thus the induced order is not guaranteed to be linear.

    Usage example: 

     
 import java.util.Comparator;
 import java.util.List;
 import java.util.Map;
 import java.util.SortedMap;
 import java.util.TreeMap;
 
 
     
 Map<K, V> unsorted;
 List<K> preferenceList;
 Comparator<K> comparator = new PreferenceListComparator<>(preferenceList);
 SortedMap<K, V> sorted = new TreeMap<>(comparator);
 sorted.putAll(unsorted);
    Author:
    Filip Bartek

      • compare

        public int compare(T o1,
                   T o2)
        Compares its two arguments for order. Returns a negative integer, zero, or a positive integer as the first argument is less than, equal to, or greater than the second.

        Note that this implementation violates some of the requirements imposed by the Comparator interface, so care should be taken when using it. In practice, it at least allows a TreeMap initialized by a Comparator to be used for one-time ordering of elements of a Map (using the method TreeMap.putAll(Map)). Other uses of the comparator have not been tested.

        Specified by:
